Certainly! Below is a TikZ LaTeX code that creates a cartoon plot depicting two bulk regions \( N_{\text{I}} \) and \( N_{\text{II}} \), each dual to a Conformal Field Theory (CFT), with an interface brane \( Q \) in between.

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=5mm]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric, arrows.meta}

\tikzset{
    node distance=2cm,
    block/.style={rectangle, draw, fill=blue!30, text width=6em, text centered, rounded corners, minimum height=4em},
    line/.style={->, thick, >=stealth'}
}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[auto]

    % Nodes
    \node [block] (bulk1) {CFT$_{\text{I}}$};
    \node [block, below of=bulk1] (interface) {Interface Brane $Q$};
    \node [block, below of=interface] (bulk2) {CFT$_{\text{II}}$};

    % Arrows
    \draw [line] (bulk1.south) -- (interface.north);
    \draw [line] (interface.south) -- (bulk2.north);

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **Nodes**: 
  - `bulk1` represents \( N_{\text{I}} \) and is labeled "CFT$_{\text{I}}$".
  - `interface` represents the interface brane \( Q \) and is labeled "Interface Brane $Q$".
  - `bulk2` represents \( N_{\text{II}} \) and is labeled "CFT$_{\text{II}}$".

- **Arrows**:
  - An arrow points from `bulk1` to `interface`, indicating the direction of interaction.
  - Another arrow points from `interface` to `bulk2`, indicating the direction of interaction.

This code will produce a simple but effective cartoon diagram that clearly distinguishes the two bulk regions and their interface. You can compile this code using a LaTeX editor that supports TikZ to generate the image.

